      <div class="verdict" id="quick-verdict">
        <strong>Quick verdict:</strong> The <strong>Logitech Brio 4K</strong> is the best webcam under $150 in 2026. Sharp 4K30 video, RightLight 3 HDR that actually handles backlit windows, 5x digital zoom that stays sharp through 3x, and Windows Hello IR for face unlock. There are better webcams at twice the price, but for most remote workers the Brio is the right call.
      </div>

      <p>The Logitech Brio 4K launched in 2017 and has somehow remained the default webcam recommendation for six years. That is unusual in tech — most products in this category get replaced every 18 months. The Brio has held on because Logitech got the fundamentals right: a sharp 4K sensor, reliable autofocus, and a sturdy mount. The 2026 landscape has more competition, but the Brio still wins for most buyers.</p>

      <p>We ran the Brio on our primary workstation for 90 days of daily remote work — internal standups, client calls, recorded video, and after-hours low-light tests. We compared it head to head with the Logitech C920x ($69), Insta360 Link ($299), Anker PowerConf C200 ($55), and Razer Kiyo Pro ($149). Here is what we found.</p>

      <p>If you want the short version: the Brio is the right pick for most people, but it is not flawless. Below we break down where it earns its price and where it shows its age. For a wider field of options, see our <a href="/reviews/best-webcam-remote-work/">best webcam for remote work</a> roundup.</p>

      <h2 id="pros-and-cons">Product Summary</h2>
      <ProductSummary pros={pros} cons={cons} bestFor={bestFor} notFor={notFor} />

      <h2 id="who-should-buy">Who Should Buy This</h2>
      <p>See the summary above for a quick breakdown of who this product is best for and who should skip it.</p>

      <h2 id="detailed-review">Detailed Review</h2>

      <h3>Image Quality: 4K30 and 1080p60</h3>
      <p>The Brio's headline feature is its 4K sensor, and it delivers. In good lighting the Brio produces sharp video with fine detail in hair, fabric, and skin texture that no 1080p webcam can match. We compared the Brio side by side with the Logitech C920x (a 1080p webcam) in the same lighting, and the difference was visible on every call. Faces looked natural rather than smeared, and text on a whiteboard behind the subject stayed readable.</p>

      <p>In practice, most video conferencing platforms compress your stream to 1080p or 720p anyway. Zoom caps free accounts at 720p and requires a paid plan for 1080p; Teams and Meet typically run at 720p in group calls. So why does 4K matter? Two reasons. First, the larger sensor gathers more light, which improves low-light performance even when the output is downscaled. Second, you can crop and zoom without losing detail — the Brio's 5x digital zoom stays sharp through 3x magnification, while the C920x's 1080p sensor looks pixellated past 1.5x.</p>

      <p>The Brio also shoots 1080p60, which is useful for recorded video where you want smoother motion. We recorded a 60-second product demo at 1080p60 and the motion was noticeably smoother than 1080p30 — useful if you upload to YouTube where viewers expect 60fps.</p>

      <h3>RightLight 3 HDR: The Real Reason to Buy</h3>
      <p>RightLight 3 HDR is the feature that justifies the Brio over cheaper 4K webcams. We tested it with a bright window directly behind the camera operator and again with a window behind the subject. In both scenarios the Brio preserved face detail without blowing out the background. The C920x, with no HDR, turned faces into silhouettes against the window.</p>

      <p>This is not a small difference. If your desk faces a window — and many home offices do — the Brio is the difference between looking professional and looking like a backlit witness protection subject. We tested the Brio at noon, sunset, and after dark with a single desk lamp, and the HDR adapted smoothly across all three. The Insta360 Link matched the Brio on HDR, but the Anker C200 and Razer Kiyo Pro both struggled.</p>

      <p>If you want to take the lighting equation further, our <a href="/reviews/best-desk-lamp-eye-care/">desk lamp eye care roundup</a> covers lighting that pairs well with the Brio. Good lighting plus the Brio's HDR is the gold standard for a home office video setup.</p>

      <h3>5x Digital Zoom: How Sharp Is It?</h3>
      <p>The Brio's 5x digital zoom is software-based, not optical, but the 4K sensor makes it usable. We measured face detail at 100%, 200%, and 300% zoom on a recorded 4K clip. At 100% the image is sharp. At 200% it is still crisp enough for a tight head-and-shoulders crop. At 300% you start to see slight softening, but the image is still sharper than a 1080p webcam at 100%. At 400% and 500% the image gets noticeably soft — we recommend staying under 3x.</p>

      <p>This matters if you present to large audiences and want a tight crop, or if you record video where you want to zoom in on a product. Most casual users will not need zoom, but it is a useful feature to have.</p>

      <h3>Windows Hello IR: Face Unlock That Works</h3>
      <p>The Brio includes an IR sensor that supports Windows Hello face unlock. We tested it on a Windows 11 desktop that did not have a built-in IR camera, and it worked flawlessly — face unlock in under a second, even in a dim room. The IR sensor also enables Brio's "look away to lock" feature, which blanks the screen when you turn your head (though we found this more annoying than useful).</p>

      <p>Mac users do not get face unlock — Apple's Face ID equivalent is not exposed to third-party webcams. But the IR sensor does not interfere with normal video calls, so Mac users lose nothing by having it. If you are on Windows and want face unlock without buying a new laptop, the Brio is the cheapest way to get it.</p>

      <h3>Dual Noise-Canceling Mics: Better Than Expected</h3>
      <p>The Brio has two omnidirectional microphones with noise cancellation, and they are the best mics of any webcam we tested. Voices sound clear and room echo is reduced compared to the C920x. The Anker PowerConf C200's mic array is comparable, and the Insta360 Link is slightly better. None of them match a dedicated USB mic — a $50 Blue Snowball sounds noticeably richer.</p>

      <p>Our recommendation: use the Brio's mic for internal standups and pair the camera with a dedicated mic for client calls or recorded video. If you wear a headset with a boom mic, your headset will beat any webcam mic — use that. The Brio's mics are a good fallback when you do not have a dedicated mic handy.</p>

      <h3>Field of View: 65, 78, and 90 Degrees</h3>
      <p>The Brio offers 65, 78, and 90 degree field of view options through Logi Tune. The default 65 degree is too tight for two people sitting at one desk — we measured roughly 4 feet of horizontal coverage at 3 feet distance. The 78 degree is the sweet spot for solo work, framing a head and shoulders with a bit of background. The 90 degree shows your whole desk and is best for showcasing a workspace or including a partner.</p>

      <p>Wide field of view distorts faces at the edges (barrel distortion), which is why we avoid 90 degree for daily calls. The Insta360 Link defaults to 79 degrees and crops in software to 65 or 55 if you want a tighter shot. The Anker C200 has a fixed 95 degree field of view that we found too wide for solo calls — it makes your face look small and your room look messy.</p>

      <h3>Build Quality and Mounting</h3>
      <p>The Brio is a small, dense webcam with a matte plastic body and a glass front element. The clip is sturdy, with a rubber pad that grips both flat and curved monitors. We tested it on a flat 27-inch monitor, a 34-inch curved ultrawide, and a 13-inch laptop, and it stayed put on all three. The clip tilts but does not pan — if you need horizontal adjustment, you have to move the whole webcam.</p>

      <p>The Brio has a standard 1/4-inch tripod thread on the bottom, so you can mount it on a small tripod or a monitor arm if your monitor does not have a flat top edge. The included USB-C cable is 5 feet long, which is enough to reach a desktop under the desk but tight if you want to route it through a cable manager.</p>

      <p>A <a href="/reviews/best-monitor-riser-desk/">monitor riser</a> lifts both monitor and webcam to eye level — a webcam that sits below your eye line shoots up your nostrils and looks unprofessional. If you use a laptop, a <a href="/reviews/best-laptop-stand-desk/">laptop stand</a> does the same job and prevents neck strain.</p>

      <h3>Software: Logi Tune</h3>
      <p>The Brio works plug-and-play on macOS, Windows, ChromeOS, and most Linux distributions — no drivers required. But to unlock 4K resolution, zoom presets, color tuning, and field of view switching, you need Logi Tune, which is available for both Mac and Windows. The software is free, lightweight, and runs in the background without nagging.</p>

      <p>Logi Tune is genuinely useful. We used it to set a custom color profile that matched our daylight bulbs, and we saved a zoom preset that framed our head and shoulders at 1.5x magnification. The software also lets you disable the IR sensor's "look away to lock" feature, which we did on day one.</p>

      <h2 id="comparison">How It Compares to the Competition</h2>
      <p>We tested four competing webcams head to head. Here is how the top three stack up:</p>

      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
