      <p>The Insta360 Link is the only webcam that clearly beats the Brio, and only on auto-framing and design. Its three-axis gimbal and AI tracking are unmatched, and the image quality is marginally sharper in low light. But it costs $170 more and requires USB 3.0 for 4K. If you present while standing or walking, the Link is worth it. If you sit at a desk, the gimbal is wasted money.</p>

      <p>The Razer Kiyo Pro is the Brio's closest competitor on price. It shoots 1080p60 (no 4K) but has a larger sensor that performs well in low light. The Kiyo Pro lacks HDR and Windows Hello IR, which are the two main reasons to pick the Brio. We recommend the Kiyo Pro only if you stream and want 60fps without paying for 4K you will not use.</p>

      <p>The Logitech C920x remains the value benchmark at $69. It shoots 1080p30, has a 78-degree field of view, and includes a single mic. If you only take a few calls per week in a well-lit room, the C920x is fine. The Brio is meaningfully better, but the C920x is half the price.</p>

      <h2 id="buying-advice">Buying Advice</h2>
      <p>Buy the Logitech Brio 4K if you spend more than 5 hours per week on video calls. The image quality, HDR, and Windows Hello IR earn back the $129 within a month of daily use, and the webcam will outlast several laptops. The Brio is a buy-it-for-years purchase.</p>

      <p>Verify your computer's USB ports before buying. 4K requires USB 3.0 or USB-C; on USB 2.0 the Brio drops to 1080p30. Most modern laptops and monitors have USB 3.0 or USB-C, but older desktops and budget laptops may not. The Brio ships with both USB-A and USB-C cables, so you do not need to buy an adapter.</p>

      <p>Check your video conferencing platform's resolution caps. Zoom caps free accounts at 720p and requires a paid plan for 1080p. Teams and Meet typically run at 720p in group calls. You will still benefit from the Brio's larger sensor and HDR even at 720p output, but you will not see the full 4K unless you record video or present to large audiences.</p>

      <p>Buy from a retailer with a 30-day return window. The Brio is excellent, but the right webcam depends on your face shape, room lighting, and call platform. If the Brio's 65-degree default field of view feels too tight and you do not want to install Logi Tune, return it and exchange it for the Insta360 Link or the Razer Kiyo Pro.</p>

      <p>Finally, fix your lighting before buying a more expensive webcam. A $50 webcam in a well-lit room looks better than a $300 webcam in a dark room. Our <a href="/reviews/best-desk-lamp-eye-care/">desk lamp eye care guide</a> covers the lighting side of the equation. If you want a wider field of options, our <a href="/reviews/best-webcam-work-from-home/">best webcam for work from home</a> roundup covers picks tuned for at-home lighting conditions.</p>

